th%20Congress.pdf |title= Once a Soldier... Always a Soldier |year= 2011 |work= Legislative Agenda |publisher= [[Association of the United States Army]] |accessdate= January 27, 2013 |deadurl= yes |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131021200011/http://www.ausa.org/legislation/congressionalinfo/Documents/OAS%20112th%20Congress.pdf |archivedate= October 21, 2013}}</ref>\n|rank         = [[File:Army-USA-OR-05.svg|18px]] [[Sergeant]]\n|unit         = [[United States Marine Corps Reserve]]<br>[[Mississippi Army National Guard]]\n|battles      = [[Gulf War]]<br>[[Iraq War]]\n}}\n\n'''Steven McCarty Palazzo''' {{IPAc-en|p|\u0259|\u02c8|l|\u0251\u02d0|z|o\u028a}} (born February 21, 1970) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|MS|4}} since 2011. The district takes in [[Mississippi]]'s Gulf Coast and includes [[Biloxi]], [[Gulfport, Mississippi|Gulfport]], [[Pascagoula]], [[Laurel, Mississippi|Laurel]] and [[Hattiesburg, Mississippi|Hattiesburg]]. Palazzo is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. \n\nHe defeated 10-term [[Democratic Party (US)|Democratic]] [[incumbent]] [[Gene Taylor (Mississippi)|Gene Taylor]] with 52% to 47% of the vote in the 2010 mid-term election. Previously, he served in the [[Mississippi House of Representatives]], having represented District 116 from 2006 to 2011. Palazzo again defeated Taylor in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Mississippi, 2014|June 2014 Republican primary election]]. Taylor switched parties in a bid to return to his former House seat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/senate-races/199634-ex-rep-gene-taylor-becomes-republican-to-run-again|title=Cameron Joseph, Ex-Rep. switches parties to run again|publisher=Thehill.com|accessdate=March 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and military service==\nPalazzo was born February 21, 1970 in Gulfport.<ref name=\"state1\">{{cite web|url=http://billstatus.ls.state.ms.us/members/house/palazzo.xml |accessdate=June 3, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100511074353/http://billstatus.ls.state.ms.us/members/house/palazzo.xml |archivedate=May 11, 2010 }}</ref> \n\nHe enlisted in the [[Marine Corps Reserve]] in 1988, and served with the [[3rd Force Reconnaissance Company]] in the [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]]. He currently serves in the [[Mississippi Army National Guard]]. He received a [[Bachelor's]] and [[Master of Accountancy|MPA]] from the [[University of Southern Mississippi]], and is a member of the [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity. He graduated from [[Gulfport High School]] in 1988. He is a [[Certified Public Accountant]].{{cn|date=July 2018}}\n\n==Mississippi House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\nIn April 2006, incumbent Republican State Representative Leonard Bentz of Mississippi's 116th House District resigned because he was appointed to the [[Mississippi Public Service Commission]]. Palazzo defeated Democratic candidate Maryann Graczyk, an education lobbyist, and Republican George Emile, a funeral home director, 51%\u201326%\u201324%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=396624 |title=MS State House 116 \u2013 Special Election Race \u2013 Nov 07, 2006 |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-14}}</ref> In 2007, running unopposed, he was elected to a full term.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=396601 |title=MS State House 116 Race |date= November 6, 2007 |publisher= Ourcampaigns.com |accessdate= 2015-03-14}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nPalazzo was awarded the 2009 Elected Official of the Year from the MS Wildlife Federation. The ''Mississippi Business Journal'' and the ''Sun Herald'' (2005) named Palazzo as a Top Business Leader under 40.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://palazzoforcongress.com/about-steven-palazzo |title=Steven Palazzo \u2013 U.S. Congress |publisher=Palazzoforcongress.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-14}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nHe served on the Banking and Financial Services, Juvenile Justice, Labor, Select Committee on the Gulf Coast Disaster, and the Wildlife, Fisheries and Parks Committees.<ref name=\"state1\"/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n\n====2010====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Mississippi, 2010#District 4}}\nPalazzo entered the Republican primary for [[Mississippi's 4th congressional district]] and won the nomination with 57% of the vote. He faced 10-term Democratic incumbent [[Gene Taylor (Mississippi)|Gene Taylor]] in the general election. \n\nAlthough the 4th had turned almost solidly Republican at the federal level, Taylor held the seat without serious difficulty from 1996 onward. His voting record had been very conservative even by [[Mississippi Democratic Party|Mississippi Democratic]] standards, and he'd often broken with his party. Palazzo established himself as Taylor's strongest opponent since 1996. In particular, he attacked Taylor for supporting [[Nancy Pelosi]] for House Speaker in 2006 and 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1010/44119.html|title=Taylor: I voted for McCain \u2013 Jessica Taylor|publisher=Politico.Com|accessdate=2010-11-03}}</ref> He was endorsed by [[Sarah Palin]] and in the November 2010 general election, Palazzo defeated Taylor 52%\u201347%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=496790 |title=MS \u2013 District 04 Race \u2013 Nov 02, 2010 |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-14}}</ref>\n\n====2012====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Mississippi, 2012#District 4}}\nIn the Republican primary, he defeated two challengers with 74% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=751580 |title=MS District 04 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Mar 13, 2012 |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-14}}</ref> In the November election, he defeated Democratic candidate Matthew Moore 64%\u201329%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=724373 |title=MS \u2013 District 04 Race \u2013 Nov 06, 2012 |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-14}}</ref>\n\n====2014====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Mississippi, 2014#District 4}}\nIn the Republican primary, Palazzo faced four challengers, including his predecessor, Taylor. Palazzo won 50.5% of the vote while Taylor won 43% of the vote. Three minor candidates made up the remaining percentage. Taylor actively campaigned and drew large numbers of Democrats into the Republican primary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://msbusiness.com/blog/2014/06/05/palazzo-defeats-taylor-4th-congressional-district-primary/ |title=Palazzo defeats Taylor in 4th Congressional District primary|publisher=Msbusiness.com |date=2014-06-05 |accessdate=2015-03-14}}</ref> Palazzo was targeted by the [[Club for Growth]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Jaffe |first=Alexandra |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/285193-club-for-growth-targeting-rino-republicans |title=Club for Growth targeting 9 'RINO' Republicans for primary challenges \u2013 The Hill's Ballot Box |publisher=Thehill.com |date=February 27, 2013 |accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn Nov. 4th 2014, Palazzo easily defeated his 2012 opponent, Matt Moore, 69.9% to 24.3%; four minor party or independent candidates accounted for 3.8% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.ms.gov/Elections-Voting/Pages/2014-General-Elections.aspx |title=2014 General Elections |publisher=Sos.ms.gov |date= |accessdate=2015-03-14}}</ref>\n\n====2016====\nIn the Republican primary, Palazzo ran unopposed for the first time in his political career.  On November 8, Palazzo garnered 65.2% of the vote defeating Democrat Mark Gladney and two minor candidates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/house/mississippi/ |title=2016 Mississippi House Election Results|date=2016-11-11 |accessdate=2016-11-12}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nPalazzo voted with his Republican colleagues to pass a Balanced Budget Amendment, and force to repeal the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]].\n\nIn February 2017, Palazzo began to face calls from constituents to attend town halls. One on the Gulf Coast in [[Long Beach, Mississippi|Long Beach]] was organized. A similar meeting was organized in [[Hattiesburg, Mississippi|Hattiesburg]]. Palazzo did not attend either.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wlox.com/story/34602392/town-hall-crowd-gathers-in-long-beach-lawmakers-no-show|title=Town hall crowd gathers in Long Beach, lawmakers no-show|last=Keeton|first=Hugh|access-date=2017-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sunherald.com/news/politics-government/article133609424.html|title=Where\u2019s Steven Palazzo? Congressman elusive for some Coast constituents|newspaper=sunherald|access-date=2017-02-25}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nPalazzo was one of the initial co-sponsors of the [[Social Media Working Group Act of 2014 (H.R. 4263; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would direct the [[United States Secretary of Homeland Security]] to establish within the [[United States Department of Homeland Security]] (DHS) a [[social media]] working group (the Group) to provide guidance and best practices to the [[Emergency management|emergency preparedness and response]] community on the use of social media technologies before, during, and after a [[terrorist attack]].<ref name=4263sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4263 \u2013 Summary|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4263|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=July 7, 2014}}</ref> \n\nPalazzo stated that \"social media has played a crucial role in emergency preparedness and response in Mississippi, including during disasters like Hurricane Isaac and the tornadoes that hit the Hattiesburg area a little over a year ago.\"<ref name=WXXVreport>{{cite news|last1=Thomas|first1=Rachael|title=Palazzo Introduces Social Media Emergency Response Bill|url=http://www.wxxv25.com/news/local/story/Palazzo-Introduces-Social-Media-Emergency/oXdyZRilcE282zWtHC9_qg.cspx|accessdate=9 July 2014|publisher=Fox News 25 \u2013 WXXV|date=17 March 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140711083527/http://www.wxxv25.com/news/local/story/Palazzo-Introduces-Social-Media-Emergency/oXdyZRilcE282zWtHC9_qg.cspx|archivedate=11 July 2014|df=}}</ref> He said that their goal with the bill was to \"build upon existing public-private partnerships and use social media in a more strategic way in order to help save lives and property.\"<ref name=\"WXXVreport\"/>\n\nOn April 7, 2014, Palazzo introduced the [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration Authorization Act of 2014 (H.R. 4412; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would [[authorization bill|authorize]] the [[appropriations bill (United States)|appropriation]] of $17.6 billion in fiscal year 2014 to the [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] (NASA).<ref name=4412sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4412 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4412|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=9 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=cbo4412>{{cite web|title=CBO \u2013 H.R. 4412|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45376|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=9 June 2014}}</ref> NASA would use the funding for human exploration of space, the [[Space Launch System]], the [[Orion (spacecraft)|Orion multipurpose crew vehicle]], the commercial crew program, the [[International Space Station]] (ISS), and various technological and educational projects.<ref name=\"4412sum\"/><ref name=HillNASAreauth>{{cite news|last1=Marcos|first1=Cristina|title=House passes NASA reauthorization|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/208739-house-passes-nasa-reauthorization|accessdate=10 June 2014|publisher=The Hill|date=9 June 2014}}</ref> Palazzo said that \"American leadership in space depends on our ability to put people and sound policy ahead of politics.\"<ref name=\"HillNASAreauth\"/>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Readiness|Subcommittee on Readiness]]\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Space and Aeronautics|Subcommittee on Space and Aeronautics]] (Chairman)\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Research and Science Education|Subcommittee on Research and Science Education]]\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Investigations and Oversight|Subcommittee on Investigations and Oversight]]\n\n==Personal life==\nPalazzo divorced the former Lisa M. Belvin in April 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/gop-congressman-steve-palazzo-drowning-in-controversy_us_59f9e477e4b0de896d3f2cf1|title=GOP Congressman, Steve Palazzo, Drowning In Controversy|last=Bryan|first=Roger|date=2017-11-01|website=Huffington Post|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref> He is a member of the Rotary, VFW,  NRA, MS Society of CPAs, USM Alumni Association; Boys & Girls Club Board Member; Marine Corps Association and AICPA.\n\n==Controversy==\nPrior to the 2016 general election, Libertarian challenger Ric McCluskey accused Palazzo of not being truthful about his service in the National Guard, claiming Palazzo failed to show up for mandatory drills.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.myfox23.com/single-post/2016/11/01/Ric-McCluskey-claims-Palazzo-went-AWOL-during-National-Guard|title=myfox23.com|website=myfox23.com|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref>  \n\nMississippi State Representative [[David Baria]], a Democrat, sent a letter to the National Guard inquiring them to looking into Palazzo\u2019s hours of service.  Baria said the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) was investigating the claims.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wxxv25.com/2016/11/07/rep-david-baria-says-fbi-investigating-claims-palazzo-went-awol|title=Rep. David Baria Says FBI Investigating into Claims that Palazzo went AWOL|date=2016-11-07|work=WXXV 25|access-date=July 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPalazzo denied the claims, stating, \"This is a ridiculous accusation and a desperate attempt to smear a soldier\u2019s service solely for political gain.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wxxv25.com/2016/10/28/national-guard-looks-claims-congressman-steven-palazzo/|title=National Guard Looks into Claims against Congressman Steven Palazzo |date=2016-10-28|work=WXXV 25|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref>\n\nOn August 3, 2017, Republican challenger E. Brian Rose presented documents he said raised questions about Palazzo's military service record.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sunherald.com/news/politics-government/election/article165179757.html|title=Republican challenger Brian Rose says if anyone should be ashamed, it\u2019s Steven Palazzo|work=sunherald|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref>  \n\nRose claimed the documents revealed Palazzo fraudulently sought discharge from the National Guard, based on false claims of financial, family, and community hardships. ABC affiliate [[WLOX]] verified Rose's documents, stating, \"WLOX has verified through an independent source that the documents are authentic.\"<ref name=WLOX>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wlox.com/story/36056118/congressional-candidate-releases-documents-on-rep-palazzos-military-record|title=Congressional candidate releases documents on Rep. Palazzo's military record|last=Elliott|first=David|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref> Palazzo acknowledged the documents by saying, \"Not once have I ever denied that I requested this waiver more than a decade ago\", but went on to call the revelation a \"disgusting\" attack on his family and his character.<ref name=WLOX />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography|Mississippi|Politics|United States Marine Corps|United States Army}}\n* [http://palazzo.house.gov Congressman Steven Palazzo] official U.S. House site\n* [https://palazzoforcongress.com/ Campaign site]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Mississippi/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Steven_Palazzo_%5BR-4%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Steven Palazzo}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=P000601 | votesmart=69521 | fec=H0MS04120 | congress=steven-palazzo/2035 }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://ballotpedia.org/Steven_Palazzo Biography] at [[Ballotpedia]]\n* [http://www.nndb.com/people/541/000257767 Biography] at [[NNDB]]\n* [http://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/412443 Congressional profile] at [[GovTrack]]\n* [http://www.opencongress.org/people/show/412443 Congressional profile] at [[Participatory Politics Foundation|OpenCongress]]\n* [http://www.rollcall.com/members/31432.html Congressional profile] at ''[[Roll Call]]''\n* [http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00031958 Financial information (federal office)] at [[Center for Responsive Politics|OpenSecrets.org]]\n* [https://apps.washingtonpost.com/politics/capitol-assets/member/steven-palazzo/ Financial investments (personal)] at ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n* [http://www.legistorm.com/member/2768/Rep_Steven_Palazzo_MS.html Staff salaries, trips and personal finance] at LegiStorm.com\n* [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/uniquecandidate.phtml?uc=8965 Financial information (state office)] at the National Institute for Money in State Politics\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Steven_Palazzo.htm Issue positions and quotes] at [[On the Issues]]\n* [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/stevenpalazzo Appearances] on [[C-SPAN]] programs\n* [http://www.imdb.com/name/nm5149797 Appearances] at the [[Internet Movie Database]]\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/gIQAlE0YMP_topic.html Collected news and commentary] at ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n* -->\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gene Taylor (Mississippi politician)|Gene Taylor]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Mississippi's 4th congressional district]]|years=2011\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kristi Noem]]<br>R-[[South Dakota]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=223rd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Renacci]]<br>R-[[Ohio]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{MS-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palazzo, Steven}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American Marine Corps personnel of the Gulf War]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Mississippi House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Mississippi National Guard personnel]]\n[[Category:Mississippi Republicans]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Biloxi, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:People from Gulfport, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps reservists]]\n[[Category:University of Southern Mississippi alumni]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]"}]}}}}